Briefly describe the electrolytes that are important in normal body function 

Significant electrolytes are: 

Primarily interstitial 

-Na 

-Cl 

Primarily intracellular 

-K 

-Mg 

-P 

-S 

 

Define osmolality and osmolarity 

Osmolality: high solute concentration = high osmolality. High plasma osmolality means water wants to move toward the plasma. 

 

Osmolarity: measured as osmol/L. An osmole defines the number of moles of solute that contributes to the osmotic pressure of a solution. 

 

Note that osmoreceptors are activated by elevated osmolality. Osmoreceptors are inhibited by decreased osmolality. 

 

 

Define isotonic, hypotonic and hypertonic solutions and briefly describe the effect of each on a cell (such as an RBC) 

-Isotonic = osmotic pressure of intracellular fluid = osmotic pressure of interstitial fluid, or osmotic pressure across the membrane between two solutions is equal for both solutions 

-Hypertonic = osmotic pressure out of cell is greater, due to lower salt concentration in cell 

-Hypotonic = osmotic pressure into cell is greater, due to high salt concentration in cell 

 

Briefly describe the consequences to normal cellular function from alterations in sodium concentration or potassium concentrations 

Sodium imbalance 

A common site for volume depletion (increased [sodium]) and sodium loss (decreased [sodium]) is through the GIT, via diarrhea or vomiting.  

 

Hyponatremia (low blood sodium) is caused by excessive fluid intake, fluid retention due to kidney problems, or the excessive loss of sodium through chronic, severe diarrhea/vomiting. This is associated with headache, nausea, vomiting, cramps, seizures, confusion, coma. 

 

Hypernatremia (high blood sodium) is caused by water deprivation or excessive fluid loss due to diuretics, diabetes, CNS disorders. When relative water loss exceeds sodium loss, we get hypernatremia. It is associated with thirst, confusion, and hypertension. 

 

Potassium imbalance 

Potassium is a major intracellular cation. Serum potassium is maintained by a balance between absorption and excretion, which is under hormonal control of aldosterone.  

 

Hyperkalemia is caused by aldosterone deficiency, renal disease, acidosis, hemolysis, potassium-sparing diuretics, and causes abdominal cramping, fatigue, lethargy, muscle weakness or paralysis, and slower cardiac impulse conduction if severe.  

 

Hypokalemia can be caused by lack of dietary potassium, vomiting, potassium-depleting diuretics, salt-wasting kidney disease, high aldosterone. Symptoms include weakness, nausea, cramping, constipation, palpitations, hypertension, alkalosis.  

 

Note that when aldosterone is released due to decreased sodium or increased potassium levels, aldosterone signals to kidneys to reabsorb sodium and increase excretion of potassium. 

 

Note: alkalosis also causes hypokalemia.

Describe the mechanisms of water and electrolyte absorption/secretion in the small and large bowel 

Water movement across the intestinal epithelium is driven by osmotic pressure, provided by the selective distribution of Na+, K+, and Cl- ions across compartments. Water molecules move through the small and large bowel via either the paracellular or transcellular route: 

 

 

The transcellular route involves water passing directly through cell membranes and also through water channels (aquaporins). The paracellular route involves water passing between cells, through "loose" tight junctions. Tight junctions are loose in upper intestine, and tighter in lower small intestine and colon. Hence, paracellular transport decreases when getting towards the colon. Note that ions can also travel through the tight junction. 

 

From the lumen, water goes through the 4 compartments: 

Lumen <=> Intestinal cell <=> Interstitial space <=> Capillary lumen 

 

Note that in the small intestine, sodium absorption is coupled with glucose and amino acid absorption through symporters.  

 

 

 

 

Note that the basolateral Na+/K+ ATPase provides the driving force for most absorption and secretion across the apical membrane. 

 

 

 

 

CFTR channel 

Chlorine secretion in the small and large intestines occurs via crypt cells. Cl- enters cell through basolateral membrane by co-transport with Na+ and K+. (Sodium potassium pump pumping sodium out provides driving force for this process.) CFTR is a cAMP-activated, ATP-gated Cl- channel which allows Cl- to flow out of the apical membrane along the electrochemical gradient. Adenylyl cyclase is responsible for cAMP production. Na+ is also secreted to maintain electrochemical balance, drawing H2O out of the apical membrane via osmosis. A CFTR mutation can block movement of NaCl and H2O to the lumen, resulting in buildup of thick, sticky mucus. 

 

 

Describe the effect of vomiting and/or diarrhea on electrolyte and acid-base balance 

Diarrhea 

In acute diarrhea, isotonic dehydration can occur where there is a balanced depletion of water and sodium from extracellular fluid, hence resulting in no osmotic shift of water from intracellular fluid to extracellular fluid. During diarrhea, there is a large loss of HCO3- into the GI tract, which is then excreted. Hence, acidosis occurs.  

 

Blood acidosis leads to: 

-Metabolic acidosis due to decreased renal function and excretion of acid 

-Bicarbonate depletion 

-Hypokalemia  due to Na+ exchange with K+ at kidneys 

-Hyperchloremia due to exchange with bicarbonate 

-Some loss of Na+ through Na+/K+ pump in attempt to compensate 

-High creatinine due to decreased glomerular filtration rate 

 

Vomiting 

Vomiting causes fluid loss through: 

-Fluid taken by mouth 

-Ejection of gastric juices 

-Inhibition of further fluid intake 

 

Upon stimulation to vomit, parietal cells secrete H+ and Cl- (HCl). Cl- is sourced from blood, and thus at the basolateral membrane Cl- is exchanged with HCO3-.
